<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/53266163-ed-g"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/53266163-ed-g">Ed G</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I totally agree with you. Cronin goes overboard with his descriptions and ends up killing the pace and rhythm of the book. Many of his side trips and <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I totally agree with you. Cronin goes overboard with his descriptions and ends up killing the pace and rhythm of the book. Many of his side trips and descriptions are completely pointless to the story. When he spent pages describing Amy's nun's background, for example, made me wonder whether this character was vital to the story. It wasn't.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
